Dataset ds001_breast: 50000 patients, 77 opaque features, outcome pfs_months.
The identifier column patient_id was ignored. Mean pfs_months was 4.6929 months (SD 2.4958, range 0 to 16.66).

Main effects:
The dominant univariable and adjusted main effect was feature_044. In the all-main-effects model, each 1-SD increase in feature_044 corresponded to +1.7485 months of pfs_months (p=<1e-300).
Other strong adjusted main effects were feature_027 (-0.79403 months/SD), feature_039 (-0.70933 months/SD), feature_046 (+0.52471 months/SD), feature_015 (-0.2971 months/SD), feature_037 (-0.29651 months/SD), feature_031 (-0.277 months/SD), feature_004 (+0.23827 months/SD), feature_062 (-0.22978 months/SD), feature_069 (+0.24414 months/SD), and feature_063 (-0.18134 months/SD), all with very small p-values.
A smaller independent negative effect for feature_033 was also present (-0.041874 months/SD, p=1.99e-16). Nominal small effects for feature_005, feature_032, feature_017, and feature_059 were much weaker and should be treated as secondary.

Interaction and subgroup heterogeneity:
An exhaustive pairwise screen of standardized two-feature products found a concentrated interaction pattern. After adjustment for all 77 main effects, the largest valid interactions involved feature_046 with feature_031 (-0.37782 months per SD-product), feature_069 (+0.34126), feature_062 (-0.30784), feature_063 (-0.24571), and feature_010 (+0.23542), all p<1e-300.
A joint model containing all main effects plus the top 20 interaction candidates preserved the same feature_046-centered heterogeneity for feature_031 by feature_046 (-0.37633), feature_069 by feature_046 (+0.33232), feature_062 by feature_046 (-0.30148), and feature_063 by feature_046 (-0.24549). The feature_010 by feature_046 term was positive in the single-interaction model but attenuated in the joint model (+0.0092389, p=0.0783), so it was not independently supported after accounting for the other interaction candidates.
Raw subgroup checks agreed directionally. For feature_031 and feature_046, the 2x2 difference-in-differences was -1.623 months, indicating the positive feature_046 contrast was attenuated when feature_031=1. For feature_069 and feature_046, the raw difference-in-differences was +1.5944 months, indicating the feature_046 contrast was amplified when feature_069=1.
For continuous feature_062, the unadjusted slope was -0.0049353 months/SD when feature_046=0 and -0.64213 months/SD when feature_046=1, matching the negative feature_062 by feature_046 interaction. For feature_044, the positive slope was weaker when feature_039=1 (1.6757 months/SD) than when feature_039=0 (+1.7867 months/SD).

Nonlinearity:
Quadratic probes suggested that the linear feature_044 effect had a statistically detectable but small curved component (0.08203 months for standardized z^2, p=5.94e-25). The feature_062 quadratic term was 0.19036 months (p=3.19e-32), much smaller than its linear and interaction terms.

Overall conclusion:
The cohort shows a strong multivariable signal for pfs_months. Main effects explain substantial variation (R^2=0.792505), and adding the leading interaction candidates increases R^2 to 0.878932. The most clinically interpretable pattern is not a single marker alone but heterogeneity around feature_046: its favorable association with pfs_months is reduced in feature_031=1 and feature_063=1 contexts, increased in feature_069=1 contexts, and coupled with a stronger adverse feature_062 slope. The apparent feature_010 enhancement was not robust in the joint interaction model.

 succeeded in 1076ms:
Dataset: ds001_breast
Rows analyzed: 50000
Outcome: pfs_months

I analyzed the local parquet file only. The cohort had mean PFS 4.693 months (SD 2.496, range 0 to 16.660). A main-effects model including all features explained a large share of outcome variation (R^2 = 0.793), and adding the strongest interactions increased explanatory fit further.

Main effects supported by both unadjusted and adjusted analyses were concentrated in a small set of features. Continuous feature_044 was the dominant positive predictor: +0.1759 months per unit unadjusted and +0.1757 months after adjustment. Ordinal feature_027 was strongly adverse, with mean PFS declining from 5.640 months at value 0 to 4.444 at value 1 and 3.289 at value 2; the adjusted linear effect was -1.172 months per category. Binary feature_039 was adverse (-1.549 adjusted months), binary feature_046 was favorable (+1.101 adjusted months), binary feature_015 was adverse (-0.983 adjusted months), continuous feature_037 was adverse (-0.0769 months per unit), binary feature_031 was adverse (-0.582 adjusted months), binary feature_069 was favorable (+0.532 adjusted months), continuous feature_004 was favorable (+0.475 months per unit), continuous feature_062 was adverse (-0.0189 months per unit), and binary feature_063 was adverse (-0.471 adjusted months).

Several unadjusted signals did not survive multivariable adjustment. Binary feature_010 appeared favorable unadjusted (+0.362 months) but was essentially null after adjustment (+0.0136 months, p=0.340). Binary feature_025 similarly dropped from an unadjusted +0.114 months to +0.0017 adjusted months (p=0.879). Smaller adjusted effects remained for feature_033 (-0.000518 months per unit, p=2.22e-16), feature_005 (-0.0936 months, p=0.012), and feature_032 (-0.0689 months, p=0.033), but these were much smaller than the primary signals.

The strongest heterogeneity centered on feature_046. The favorable feature_046 association was highly context dependent: feature_046 by feature_031 was negative (-1.665 months), feature_046 by feature_069 was positive (+1.559 months), and feature_046 by feature_063 was negative (-1.339 months), all after adjustment for all main features. Cell means supported these directions. For feature_046 and feature_031, the feature_046=1/feature_031=0 subgroup averaged 5.966 months, while the joint feature_046=1/feature_031=1 subgroup averaged only 4.352 months. For feature_046 and feature_069, the joint feature_046=1/feature_069=1 subgroup averaged 5.890 months, whereas the other cells were near 4.29 to 4.31 months. For feature_046 and feature_063, feature_046=1/feature_063=0 averaged 5.657 months, but feature_046=1/feature_063=1 averaged 4.308 months.

Feature_062 also showed marked subgroup heterogeneity. Its adverse slope was nearly absent when feature_046=0 (-0.0004) but strong when feature_046=1 (-0.0528), with an adjusted interaction of -0.0531 months per feature_062 unit. The feature_062 slope was adverse when feature_031=0 (-0.0295) but absent when feature_031=1 (+0.0003), giving a positive adjusted interaction (+0.0294). The slope was near-null when feature_069=0 (-0.0009) but adverse when feature_069=1 (-0.0263), giving a negative adjusted interaction (-0.0263). It was adverse when feature_063=0 (-0.0226) but near-null when feature_063=1 (-0.0015), giving a positive adjusted interaction (+0.0222).

Additional binary-binary interactions among the same subgroup features were supported: feature_031 by feature_069 was negative (-0.826 months), feature_031 by feature_063 was positive (+0.718 months), and feature_069 by feature_063 was negative (-0.649 months), after adjustment for all main effects. These results suggest the apparent favorable and adverse main effects are not independent; they combine in specific multi-feature patterns.

I also tested whether the feature_044 effect varied by other major predictors. The positive feature_044 slope was weaker when feature_039=1 (interaction -0.0106), weaker at higher feature_027 values (-0.00626 per feature_027 category), slightly stronger at higher feature_004 values (+0.00343), and weaker when feature_015=1 (-0.00630). These interactions were statistically significant but much smaller than the feature_046-centered interactions.

Exploratory interactions that looked plausible in lower-dimensional screens did not always persist. The feature_027 by feature_033 interaction was not significant after all-main-effect adjustment (p=0.198), and the feature_015 by feature_037 interaction was also not significant after adjustment (p=0.397).

Finally, I tested simple nonlinear terms. Feature_044 had a positive adjusted quadratic component (+0.0605 months per squared SD), and feature_062 also had a positive adjusted quadratic component (+0.0618 months per squared SD), indicating curvature around their main linear effects. In contrast, feature_037 and feature_004 did not show detectable quadratic terms in this screen.

Overall conclusion: PFS in this cohort is dominated by strong main effects for feature_044, feature_027, feature_039, feature_046, feature_015, feature_037, feature_031, feature_069, feature_004, feature_062, and feature_063, plus a coherent interaction structure involving feature_046, feature_031, feature_069, feature_063, and feature_062. Because the feature labels are de-identified, these findings should be interpreted as statistical treatment/biomarker/outcome patterns in the opaque feature space rather than as clinically named mechanisms.

 succeeded in 1085ms:
Dataset ds001_breast contains 50,000 patients, 77 opaque feature columns, and the continuous outcome pfs_months. I evaluated univariable effects, a full all-main-effects OLS model, selected subgroup contrasts, pairwise interactions, and nonlinear quadratic terms. Effect estimates are signed in months of pfs_months.

The strongest main-effect signal was feature_044. In univariable standardized OLS, each one-SD increase in feature_044 was associated with +1.7509 months of pfs_months (p<1e-300), and the all-main-effects model retained essentially the same association (+1.7485 months per SD, p<1e-300). This strongly supported the hypothesis that higher feature_044 is associated with longer PFS. The ordinal feature_027 showed the opposite pattern: each one-SD increase was associated with -0.7997 months univariately and -0.7940 months after adjustment (both p<1e-300), supporting a robust adverse gradient.

Several binary or near-binary features had clear adjusted associations. feature_039=1 was adverse (-1.5363 months univariately; -0.7093 months per SD after full adjustment, p<1e-300). feature_046=1 was favorable (+1.0981 months univariately; +0.5247 months per SD adjusted, p<1e-300). Other independently supported adverse effects included feature_015 (-0.2971 months per SD), feature_037 (-0.2965), feature_031 (-0.2770), feature_062 (-0.2298), and feature_063 (-0.1813), all with very small p-values. Independently favorable effects included feature_069 (+0.2441) and feature_004 (+0.2383), also highly significant. A smaller adjusted adverse effect for feature_033 was statistically clear (-0.0419 months per SD, p=1.99e-16). Borderline adjusted effects for feature_005, feature_032, feature_017, and feature_059 were nominally significant but much weaker.

Some apparent univariable signals did not remain independent. feature_010 and feature_025 had favorable univariable associations, but their adjusted coefficients were small and non-significant in the full main-effects model. This refuted the interpretation that those columns had strong independent main effects; their univariable patterns were better explained by correlation with stronger features.

Interaction testing showed that heterogeneity was concentrated around feature_046. In all-main-effects-adjusted pairwise interaction screens, large feature_046 interactions appeared with feature_031 (-0.3778 months per SD-product), feature_069 (+0.3413), feature_062 (-0.3078), feature_063 (-0.2457), and feature_010 (+0.2354), all p<1e-300 in single-interaction models. In a joint model containing all main effects plus the top 20 interaction candidates, the feature_046 interactions with feature_031 (-0.3763), feature_069 (+0.3323), feature_062 (-0.3015), and feature_063 (-0.2455) remained strong, whereas the feature_010 by feature_046 term attenuated to +0.0092 months (p=0.0783). Thus, the feature_010 interaction was not independently supported after accounting for the dominant interaction structure.

Raw subgroup checks supported the same directions. The feature_046 favorable contrast was much smaller when feature_031=1, giving a 2x2 difference-in-differences of -1.623 months. The feature_046 contrast was amplified when feature_069=1, with a raw difference-in-differences of +1.5944 months. For feature_062, the adverse slope was much steeper among feature_046=1 patients (-0.6421 months per SD) than among feature_046=0 patients (-0.0049 months per SD), consistent with the negative feature_062 by feature_046 interaction. For feature_044, the positive slope was weaker when feature_039=1 (+1.6757 months per SD) than when feature_039=0 (+1.7867 months per SD), suggesting modest interaction between a strong favorable continuous feature and an adverse binary context.

Nonlinearity probes found statistically detectable but secondary curvature. feature_044 had a positive quadratic component (+0.0820 months for standardized z^2, p=5.94e-25), and feature_062 had a positive quadratic component (+0.1904 months, p=3.19e-32). These nonlinear terms were much smaller than the dominant linear and interaction effects, so they refine rather than replace the main conclusions.

Overall, the data show a strong multivariable outcome signal. The all-main-effects model explained substantial variation in pfs_months (R^2=0.792505), and adding the leading interaction terms increased R^2 to 0.878932. The most important pattern is not a single opaque feature alone but a feature_046-centered interaction structure: feature_046 is favorable overall, but that association is reduced in feature_031=1 and feature_063=1 contexts, amplified in feature_069=1 contexts, and coupled with a stronger adverse feature_062 slope. Because the feature names are de-identified, these results identify treatment-biomarker-outcome-like relationships statistically but cannot assign clinical labels to the opaque features without external metadata.

 succeeded in 1138ms:
Dataset ds001_breast contains 50,000 patient records with opaque feature columns and the continuous outcome pfs_months. No missing values were encountered in the decoded Parquet data. Mean pfs_months was 4.693 months (SD 2.496; range 0 to 16.660).

The strongest main effect was feature_044: each one-unit increase was associated with about +0.176 months of PFS after adjustment for all other features (p<1e-300). Feature_027 showed a strong ordinal negative gradient: mean PFS was 5.640 months at level 0, 4.444 at level 1, and 3.289 at level 2; the adjusted linear effect was -1.172 months per level (p<1e-300).

Several binary features had large adjusted associations. Supported adverse associations included feature_039=1 (-1.549 months), feature_015=1 (-0.983 months), feature_031=1 (-0.582 months), and feature_063=1 (-0.471 months), all highly significant. Supported favorable associations included feature_046=1 (+1.101 months) and feature_069=1 (+0.532 months), also highly significant. Continuous feature_037 was adverse (-0.0769 months per unit), feature_004 was favorable (+0.475 months per unit), feature_062 was adverse (-0.0189 months per unit), and feature_033 had a small but statistically robust adverse adjusted association (-0.000518 months per unit).

Not every unadjusted signal persisted. Feature_010 had a clear unadjusted favorable difference (+0.362 months for feature_010=1), but after adjustment the effect was only +0.0136 months and not significant (p=0.340), indicating that its apparent main effect was explained by other covariates.

Interaction testing showed substantial subgroup heterogeneity centered on feature_046, feature_031, feature_069, feature_062, and feature_063. The favorable feature_046 association was strongly attenuated by feature_031 (-1.665 interaction months), feature_062 (-0.0531 per feature_062 unit), and feature_063 (-1.339), but strengthened by feature_069 (+1.559); all had p<1e-300. Feature_031 and feature_069 had a negative interaction (-0.826), while feature_031 interactions with feature_062 (+0.0294) and feature_063 (+0.718) suggested attenuation of feature_031-associated harm in those subgroups.

Additional interactions indicated that feature_062 reduced the favorable feature_069 association (-0.0263) and that feature_063 attenuated the adverse feature_062 slope (+0.0222). The positive feature_044 association was weaker when feature_039=1 (-0.0106 interaction months), at higher feature_027 levels (-0.00626), and when feature_015=1 (-0.00630). In contrast, the hypothesized feature_040 by feature_062 interaction was not supported (interaction -0.00104, p=0.216).

Overall, the cohort appears dominated by a few large main-effect gradients plus strong multivariable interactions. The most reproducible pattern was a favorable feature_044 gradient and adverse feature_027/feature_039 gradients, with treatment- or biomarker-like heterogeneity involving feature_046, feature_031, feature_069, feature_062, and feature_063.

